05555nam a22010815i 9780520921863DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209218637 a10.1525/97805209218632doi  a(DE-B1597)569351  a(OCoLC)1202625165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDC715b.W26 2000eb 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a306/.0944/36109042211 aWalz, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPulp Surrealism :bInsolent Popular Culture in Early Twentieth-Century Paris /cRobin Walz.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. -- t1. The Baedeker of Hives -- t2. The Lament of Fantômas -- t3. Murder, Mirth, and Misogyny -- t4. Is Suicide a Solution? -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn addition to its more well known literary and artistic origins, the French surrealist movement drew inspiration from currents of psychological anxiety and rebellion running through a shadowy side of mass culture, specifically in fantastic popular fiction and sensationalistic journalism. The provocative nature of this insolent mass culture resonated with the intellectual and political preoccupations of the surrealists, as Robin Walz demonstrates in this fascinating study. Pulp Surrealism weaves an interpretative history of the intersection between mass print culture and surrealism, re-evaluating both our understanding of mass culture in early twentieth-century Paris and the revolutionary aims of the surrealist movement. Pulp Surrealism presents four case studies, each exploring the out-of the-way and impertinent elements which inspired the surrealists. Walz discusses Louis Aragon's Le paysan de Paris, one of the great surrealist novels of Paris. He goes on to consider the popular series of Fantômes crime novels; the Parisan press coverage of the arrest, trial, and execution of mass-murderer Landru; and the surrealist inquiry "Is Suicide a Solution?", which Walz juxtaposes with reprints of actual suicide faits divers (sensationalist newspaper blurbs). Although surrealist interest in sensationalist popular culture eventually waned, this exploration of mass print culture as one of the cultural milieux from which surrealism emerged ultimately calls into question assumptions about the avant-garde origins of modernism itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aFrench literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular culturexHistoryx20th centuryxFrancexParis. 0aPopular culturezFrancezParisxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial change. 0aSurrealism (Literature). 4aEuropean history. 4acultural studies. 4ahistory of culture. 4ahistory. 4aintellect. 4aintellectual history. 4apopular culture. 4arealism. 4asciences and society. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aart.  aavant garde art.  acase studies.  aearly 20th century art history.  aearly 20th century french literature.  afantmes crime novels.  afantomas.  afrance.  afrench crime fiction.  afrench pop culture.  afrench press.  ahenri desire landru.  alandru.  ale paysan de paris.  aliterature.  alouis aragon.  amarcel allain.  amass culture.  amass murderer.  amass print culture.  amodernism.  amodernity.  aparis.  apierre souvestre.  apopular culture.  apsychological anxiety.  arebellion.  arevolutionary aims.  aserial killer.  asuicide.  asurrealis